In 1989, Microsoft introduced its flagship office suite, Microsoft Office. This was a bundle of separate office productivity applications, such as Microsoft Word and Microsoft Excel.  On May 22, 1990 Microsoft launched Windows 3.0. Microsoft (1990). 
     &quot; Windows 3.0 is Here&quot; (PDF) . Press release.  Retrieved on March 31, 2007.

The new version of Microsoft&apos;s operating system boasted such new features as streamlined user interface graphics and improved protected mode capability for the Intel 386 processor; it sold over 100,000 copies in two weeks.         Windows History    . Microsoft  ( June 30, 2002 )

.    Retrieved on July 03, 2006 .

Windows at the time generated more revenue for Microsoft than OS/2, and the company decided to move more resources from OS/2 to Windows.   David Both  .   OS/2 History    . OS/2 VOICE .    Retrieved on July 03, 2006 .

In the ensuing years, the popularity of OS/2 declined, and Windows quickly became the favored PC platform.

During the transition from MS-DOS to Windows, the success of Microsoft&apos;s product Microsoft Office allowed the company to gain ground on application-software competitors, such as WordPerfect and Lotus 1-2-3.         Microsoft Company 15 September 1975    . The History of Computing Project .    Retrieved on August 11 , 2005 .

Steve Masters 
      ( February 13, 1998 )

.   Behind the Pearly Gates     .  VNU Business Publications  
 .    Retrieved on July 04, 2006 .

According to The Register, Novell, an owner of WordPerfect for a time, alleged that Microsoft used its inside knowledge of the DOS and Windows kernels and of undocumented Application Programming Interface features to make Office perform better than its competitors.   Andrew Orlowski 
      ( November 16, 2004 )

